ched my deepest, dearest hopes take shape, and I am not entirely sure I like the shape they have taken.\n\n- Jacqueline Carey, Kushiel's Justice\n|\nExcuse me, Captain. Are you two going to weep salty tears of admiration over a helmet all night, or do we have matters to discuss?\n\n- Eoin Colfer, The Lost Colony\n|\nI don’t see myself being special; I just see myself having more responsibilities than the next man. People look to me to do things for them, to have answers.\n\n- Tupac\n|\nI am living in a nightmare, from which from time to time I wake in sleep.\n\n- Ursula\n|\nWhite clouds, blue sky.\n\n- Laiah\n|\nAs long as there have been women.' Mom told me, 'there have been ways to punish them for being women.\n\n- Elana\n|\nThere is only one day left, always starting over: It is given to us at dawn and taken away from us at dusk.\n\n- Jean-Paul\n|\nWhen wounds are healed by love,The scars are beautiful.\n\n- David  Bowles, Shattering and Bricolage\n|\nIf I could do it all again, I would start three hundred years ago, and write twice as fast.\n\n- Peter\n|\nWar is a monster. War is the devil. It starts and it consumes and it grows and grows. And otherwise normal men become monsters, too.\n\n- Patrick Ness, The Knife of Never Letting Go\n|\nO God, please give us grace to do the good we must do.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nDepression is like being under house arrest, only there is no house.\n\n- Lisa Eley, Thirteen Geese in Flight: One Black Woman's Ascent into Mental Illness\n|\nSome day, with the last exhaustion, peace will come. It won't be the end of all things to come.\n\n- Napz\n|\nIn my fool hardy youth, when my friends were dreaming of heroic deeds in the realms of engineering and law, finance and national politics, I dreamt of becoming a librarian.\n\n- Alberto Manguel, The Library at Night\n|\nOnce you have been tortured, you can never belong in this world. There is no place that ever be your home.\n\n- Roma Tearne, Mosquito\n|\nHow badly arranged the world is. What is the purpose of ugliness, suffering, sadness? Why our powerless dreams? Why everything?\n\n- Gustave Flaubert, Correspondance\n|\nThat is the second time you have spoken out of turn, Miss Granger,” said Snape coolly. “Five more points from Gryffindor for being an insufferable know-it-all.\n\n- J.K. Rowling, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban\n|\nThat was courage, Keller thought. Not doing something without being afraid, but doing something even though you were afraid.\n\n- L.J. Smith, Witchlight\n|\nAs man sows, so shall he reap. In works of fiction, such men are sometimes converted. More often, in real life, they do not change their natures until they are converted into dust.\n\n- Charles\n|\nGratitude must come from a place of true sincerity to be effective. Without sincerity, the experience is incomplete.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nWhen it's possible for you to dream, it's not impossible to achieve.\n\n- Udai\n|\nLook, let me just say it: He was hot. A nonhot boy stares at you relentlessly and it is, at best, awkward and, at worst, a form of assault. But a hot boy . . . well.\n\n- John Green, The Fault in Our Stars\n|\nSeems to me that for you, evangelicalism is like the boyfriend you broke up with two years ago, but whose Facebook page you still check compulsively.\n\n- Rachel Held Evans, Searching for Sunday: Loving, Leaving, and Finding the Church\n|\nIt feels like I’m stuck in one spot. It’s been this way for a long time. I know you understand, but now you’re moving on without me. And I—I’m not ready to be alone.\n\n- Brent  Jones, The Fifteenth of June\n|\nGabe?'The newchild stirred slightly in his sleep. Jonas looked over at him. 'There could be love', Jonas whispered.\n\n- Lois Lowry, The Giver\n|\nIf only we wait on God's timings, we shall eat of the best fruits from the tree of life in the garden of God.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nI loved this place when I was a kid. I still love it, but when I was a kid I'd take the bus down here and spend all day long reading in this room.\n\n- Caitlín R. Kiernan, Threshold\n|\nThe Prayer that precedes all other prayer is, may the real me meet the real you.\n\n- C.S.\n|\nA fire needs three things: a dry bed, fuel, and room to breathe.\n\n- Alexis M. Smith, Marrow Island\n|\nWe can live without religion and meditation, but we cannot survive without human affection.\n\n- Dalai\n|\nArt is an imagination, crafted over innocent dreams and vibrant integrity.\n\n- Basu\n|\nFor beautiful eyes, look for the good in others; for beautiful lips, speak only words of kindness; and for poise, walk with the knowledge that you are never alone.\n\n- Sam\n|\nAs a well spent day brings happy sleep, so life well used brings happy death.\n\n- Leonardo\n|\nHope is something God gives us. Hope is...Hope is a bright light on a dark night. If your hope is guiding you into this shore, then this is where you should drop your anchor.\n\n- Tiffany Reisz, The Night Mark\n|\nA flower is symbol of beauty for eyes, but music is the expression of beauty for ears.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nPeace is a fresh flower; when it's freshness and beauty touches heart,it will last forever.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nYou can coddle your rage, or you can fully engage.\n\n- Tony   Cleaver, A Chain of Flames\n|\nIt's so hard to forget pain, but it's even harder to remember sweetness. We have no scar to show for happiness. We learn so little from peace.\n\n- Chuck Palahniuk, Diary\n|\nIt may take little time to get where you want to be, but if you pause and think for a moment, you will notice that you are no longer where you were. Do not stop—keep going.\n\n- Rodolfo Costa, Advice My Parents Gave Me: and Other Lessons I Learned from My Mistakes\n|\nIf someone thinks that peace and love are just a cliche that must have been left behind in the 60s, that's a problem. Peace and love are eternal.\n\n- John\n|\nDoost', Ahmed voiced. 'Doost',he repeated softly,shutting his eyes.The word felt like a caress.'what does it mean?''It means 'The Friend','The One I Love','the One I Long For'.\n\n- Muriel Maufroy, Rumi's Daughter\n|\nWe must stop seeing the natural world as a commodity and start seeing it as we would see a family member, something to love, protect, care for, and cherish.\n\n- Barry Babcock, TEACHERS IN THE FOREST: Essays from the last wilderness in Mississippi Headwaters Country\n|\nMen make their own history, but they do not make it as they please.\n\n- Karl\n|\nWhoever blessings, shall be abundantly blessed.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nTo see a World in a grain of sand,And a Heaven in a wild flower,Hold Infinity in the palm of your hand,And Eternity in an hour.\n\n- William Blake, Auguries of Innocence\n|\nI'd decided to establish a new rule for myself: read for half an hour an evening, no matter what.\n\n- Zadie Smith, Swing Time\n|\nEvery morning, introduce one positive thought into your mind. Be persistent with it until it becomes your habit. It will change your life.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nWhen I leave this earthly home and go up to God to dwell, someone will look on the heaped up grave and whisper, 'She tried to do well.\n\n- Reverend Ada Slaton Bonds, Cumberland Presbyterian\n|\nAhead and to the west was our ranger station - and the mountains of Idaho, poems of geology stretching beyond any boundaries and seemingly even beyond the world.\n\n- Norman Maclean, A River Runs Through It and Other Stories\n|\nYou are brighter than the sun, prettier than a fresh flower, and sweeter than any chocolate. Your songs are always humming in my heart. I wish you a sweet sweetest day.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nHave faith, let go, and gravitate towards.\n\n- Stefan\n|\nI'd rather be interesting, original, & unique then follow the pack. Revel in who you truly are & be liberated!\n\n- Amy\n|\nThere's only one person who needs a glass of water oftener than a small child tucked in for the night, and that's a writer sitting down to write.\n\n- Mignon\n|\nOn this platform of peace, we can create a languageto translate ourselves to ourselves and to each other.