ure Buddhist Philosophy and Science\n|\nTo enjoy the song of love and beauty, just get lost in the wonders of nature.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nMen from the mountains always dream of the sea, and above all things I love to travel.\n\n- Anaïs Nin, The Four-Chambered Heart: V3 in Nin's Continuous Novel\n|\nIf you wait, your heavenly Father will pick you up, carry you out into the night, and make your life sparkle. He wants to dazzle you with the wonder of his love.\n\n- Paul E. Miller, A Praying Life: Connecting with God in a Distracting World\n|\nBooks are like oxygen to a deep-sea diver,' she had once said. 'Take them away and you might as well begin counting the bubbles.\n\n- Alan Bradley, I Am Half-Sick of Shadows\n|\nForgiveness and faith are like writing a story, they take time, effort, revisions.\n\n- Daisy Hernandez, A Cup of Water Under My Bed: A Memoir\n|\nالوقت لا يلئم الجراح، بل الحبtime does not heal wounds, love does\n\n- Wafaa\n|\nPeople Ignore, People Hurt, People Confuse. But, Nature Talks, Nature Heals, Nature Answers.\n\n- Abdur-Rehman\n|\nI found the poems in the fields,And only wrote them down.\n\n- John Clare, The Later Poems, 1837-1864: Volumes I and II\n|\nFeel nothing, know nothing, do nothing, have nothing, give up all to God, and say utterly, 'Thy will be done.' We only dream this bondage. Wake up and let it go.\n\n- Swami\n|\nif youre never scared, or embarased, or hurt, it means you never take any chances.\n\n- Julia\n|\nHe'd had his career, his triumphs. Success had brought him nothing but misery; he couldn't handle it. Success had thrown him in the gutter\n\n- John Grisham, The Testament\n|\nEven with all the Lace, you can't be an Ace without God's grace.- RVM\n\n- RVM\n|\nIf ever it's necessary to ride the bandwagon, it's done with one leg swinging out and eyes scoping the fields.\n\n- Criss Jami, Killosophy\n|\nIt was by faith, nothing wavering, that Joseph saw God our Eternal Father and Jesus Christ, His Son.\n\n- Thomas\n|\nWe both loved the